'''Mumia Abu-Jamal''' (born '''Wesley Cook''' [[April 24]], [[1954]]<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =Pennsylvania Department of Corrections
  | title =Persons sentenced to execution in Pennsylvania as of August 1, 2007
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.cor.state.pa.us/portal/lib/portal/Execution_List
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>) is a former [[Black Panther Party]] [[activist]], cab driver and local journalist from [[Philadelphia]] [[conviction|convicted]] for the [[murder]] of [[police officer]] [[Daniel Faulkner]] in 1981. He is serving a presently undefined [[Sentence (law)|sentence]] of [[imprisonment]] at State Correctional Institution - Greene near [[Waynesburg, Pennsylvania]] in consequence. Originally [[Capital punishment|sentenced to death]], that sentence was quashed and resentencing ordered in December 2001 by a [[judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania]]. Both he and the [[Commonwealth of Pennsylvania]] have [[appeal (law)|appealed]] the [[court ruling|ruling]] alternately as to the appropriateness of affirming the conviction and that of disaffirming the validity of the original sentence. 

His [[cause celebre|celebrated case]] has received [[international]] attention. Supporters and human rights campaigners variously assert that he is innocent, that the incident in question was a [[Actual innocence|setup]], that he did not receive a [[fair trial]], and/or express their opposition to the possibility of the administration of the [[death penalty]]. Skeptics and opponents assert that he is [[guilt (law)|guilty]], that he received the benefit of [[due process]] and was legitimately [[conviction|convicted]] of murder. Execution proponents among these assert that under Pennsylvania law, his eventual [[judicial execution]] is warranted and mandated by the nature of his crime.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Amnesty International: new trial
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://web.amnesty.org/library/Index/engAMR510012000 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =Court TV
  | title =Guilty and Framed 
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.courttv.com/archive/casefiles/mumia/guilty.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =European Parliament
  | title =European Parliament resolution (p. 39 of original, 49 of pdf
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.europarl.europa.eu/calendar/calendar?APP=PDF&TYPE=PV2&FILE=19950921EN.pdf&LANGUE=EN  
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

The attention received has spawned [[controversy|controversies]] surrounding references to him in [[music]] and [[toponymy|naming of public places]], as well as his status as a celebrated author, [[Honorary degree|honoree]] of [[municipal]], educational and [[civil society]] organizations, and his engagement as a [[radio host]], [[writer]] and [[commencement speaker]] in the United States.  

== Early life and political career ==
[[Image:WPhilaDistrict.PNG|thumb|right|200px|Philadelphia region map demonstrating the location of [[West Philadelphia]], which is inclusive of Powelton]][[Image:Bpp logo.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Black Panther Party logo]]Born Wesley Cook he chose the name ''Mumia Abu-Jamal'' in a [[high school]] class on [[African culture]]s, in which [[student]]s used [[classroom]] [[names]]. As an [[adult]], he formally [[adopt]]ed the name. ''Mumia'' is [[Swahili language|Swahili]] in origin. "Abu-Jamal" which means [[father]] of Jamal (the name of his [[son]]) is [[Arabic language|Arabic]] in origin. He has not at any point asserted that his choice of name relates to [[Conversion to Islam#Conversion to Islam|religious conversion to Islam]] and he has never asserted that he is a [[Muslim]].  He expresses his religious beliefs, which follow no denomination, in his [[poetry]] [[book]] "Death Blossoms", which was published by a [[Christian]] [[Monasticism|monastic]] organization. Abu-Jamal continually expresses a belief in a "Mother God" who coexists with all [[male]] religious understandings.  An example is, "You call him [[God]]; I call him Mama."<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =Abu-Jamal, Mumia
  | title =Death Blossoms
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://planetgrenada.blogspot.com/2005/05/mumia-abu-jamal-death-blossoms.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =}}
</ref>

He was an early member of the [[Black Panther Party]]'s Philadelphia Branch, rising to be the Lieutenant Minister of Information for the group's Philadelphia chapter <ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Danielfaulkner.com summary of case facts
  | work =See p.2
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/SummaryofCaseFacts.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> and a [[journalist]] known for reporting upon the now-infamous [[MOVE]] community in the city's [[Powelton Village]] neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Mediafilter.org biographical information on Mumia Abu-Jamal
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://mediafilter.org/MFF/Mumia.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> Jamal predicted that the militant activist commune would be attacked, and in 1985 the MOVE house was firebombed by police during a stand-off between MOVE members and city officials, killing 11 people and destroying an entire row of houses.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =20th Anniversary of Move Bombing
  | work =
  | publisher =Metafilter.com community weblog
  | date =May 12, 2005 
  | url =http://www.metafilter.com/41954/20th-Anniversary-of-MOVE-bombing
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

At the time of the murder of Daniel Faulkner, Jamal worked as a [[taxicab]] driver for the United Cab Company in Philadelphia and had some prior experience as a reporter for [[National Public Radio]]'s affiliate in Philadelphia.<ref>As stated in "''All Things Censored''" by Mumia Abu-Jamal (also mentioning his early journalism career)</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
