</ref>

==Murder, arrest, trial==
{{main|1982 trial of Mumia Abu-Jamal}}
{{seealso|Mumia Abu-Jamal legal proceedings}}
In the early hours of December 9, 1981, around 3:51 a.m., [[Philadelphia Police Department]] officer [[Daniel Faulkner]] was [[shooting|shot]] and [[kill]]ed during an altercation that ensued from a routine [[traffic stop]] of a vehicle driven by [[William Cook (street vendor)|William Cook]], Mumia's younger brother.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial and post-conviction relief hearing transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
 </ref> 
[[Image:Daniel faulkner.jpg|right|thumb|220px|Daniel Faulkner]]
The following sequence of events was presented in [[evidence]] by the [[prosecution]] before the [[jury]] at his [[Trial (law)|trial]]<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>: 
<blockquote>1. During the traffic stop, Cook [[assault]]ed Faulkner, who in turn attempted to subdue Cook.<br /> 
2. Abu Jamal emerged from a nearby parking lot and shot Faulkner in the [[back]].<br /> 
3. Faulkner was able to return fire, seriously [[wound]]ing Mumia.<br />
4. Abu Jamal then advanced on Faulkner, fired some additional shots at close range, one of which struck Faulkner in the [[face]] causing his [[death]].<br />  
5. Abu Jamal was unable to flee due to his own [[gunshot injury|gunshot wound]], and was taken into [[arrest|custody]] by other police officers, who had been summoned by Faulkner at the time of the traffic stop.<br /></blockquote> 

[[Image:38 Special.jpg|right|thumb|200px|.38 Special rounds]]
In Abu-Jamal's possession was a [[.38 Special|.38 caliber]] [[revolver]] that records showed he had purchased in 1979. The [[Cylinder (firearms)|cylinder]] of the revolver had five spent [[Cartridge (firearms)|cartridges]]. He was taken directly from the scene of the shooting to a [[hospital]] and was treated for his [[injury]]. [[Witness]]es, including a [[security guard]] working at the hospital, stated that while he was receiving medical treatment, he acknowledged that he [[shooting|shot]] Daniel Faulkner (see [[Mumia Abu-Jamal#"Hospital bed" confession|"Hospital bed" confession]]). The Commonwealth of Pennsylvania contends that his version of events is not supported by [[testimony]] and [[physical evidence]] brought into consideration at his trial: that, in particular, it is inconsistent with the finding that a weapon registered in his name was identified as the weapon known to have administered the fatal gunshots to Daniel Faulkner's [[body]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial and 1995-7 post-conviction relief hearing transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
 </ref> 

He was [[indictment|charged]] with [[first-degree murder]]. He initially retained the services of [[Defense (legal)|criminal defense]] [[attorney]] Anthony Jackson. In May 1982 he announced that he would [[Pro se|represent himself]], with Jackson continuing to act as his [[legal advice|legal advisor]]. The [[judge]] initially acquiesced to this but, in time, reversed his attitude of acceptance citing the effect of Mumia's deemed "disruptive" behavior in the court.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Day 1 Transcript of 1982 trial, from 1.82 for the rest of the day
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/Days/6-17-82.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> 

[[Image:Philadelphia City Hall (from Art Museum).JPG|thumb|right|180px|Philadelphia City Hall, shown in 2006]]
Mumia repeatedly and vociferously [[dissent]]ed from accepting the judge's [[court ruling|rulings]] on [[question of law|points of law]] to the extent that he was removed from representing himself and it was [[court order|ordered]] that Jackson resume the role of acting as his sole [[advocate]].<ref>http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf 1982 trial transcripts</ref> The [[Legal case|case]] went to trial in June 1982 at [[Philadelphia City Hall|Philadelphia's City Hall]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Danielfaulkner.com summary of case facts, see p.2
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/SummaryofCaseFacts.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

=== Prosecution witnesses at trial ===
Four eyewitnesses to the shooting were produced by the [[prosecution]]:
 
<blockquote>1. Robert Chobert, a [[taxicab|cab]] [[driving|driver]];<br /> 
2. Michael Scanlon, a [[businessman]] who had been visiting from out of town on the night of the killing;<br /> 
3. Cynthia White, a [[prostitute]] who was later revealed to be a [[police informant]];<br />
4. Albert Magilton, a passerby<br /></blockquote>  

These witnesses testified to the effect that they were at the scene at the time of the shooting, and each identified Abu-Jamal as the person who shot Daniel Faulkner.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
 </ref>

=== Defense witnesses at trial ===
==== "''Running man''" defense ====
A number of witnesses made statements - either to police on the scene or in court testimony or both - describing the fact of one or more men were running along the street shortly after the shooting.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =Komisar
  | first =Lucy
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Mumia Abu-Jamal 101 
  | work =
  | publisher =Albion Monitor
  | date =December 17, 1998
  | url =http://www.albionmonitor.com/9812a/mumiaback.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> At trial, the defense presented statements made by four of these witnesses: Deborah Kordansky, Robert Chobert, Veronica Jones, and Desie Hightower.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>  

This became known as the "running man theory", based on the possibility that a "running man" may have been the actual shooter. Of those witnesses, only Chobert averred to actually witnessing the shooting. He testified that shortly after the shooting he had told police that he had seen Abu-Jamal shoot Daniel Faulkner in the face, and that Abu-Jamal had then run a short distance and collapsed on the sidewalk - himself having also been shot by Faulkner.  In other words, Chobert's testimony was that ''Abu-Jamal himself'' was the running man.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>  

The remaining three witnesses made various statements about a man or men running in or away from the area. None of them claimed that the running man, or men, were involved in the shooting.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
 </ref>

==== "''Hospital bed''" confession ====
The defense presented three additional witnesses: security officer Priscilla Durham and two members of the [[Philadelphia Police Department]], all of whom testified that while he was being treated for gunshot wounds he had twice proclaimed:{{cquote|I shot the [[motherfucker]], and I hope the motherfucker dies.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Bissinger
  | first =Buzz 
  | coauthors =
  | title =The Famous And The Dead
  | work =
  | pages =p.10
  | language =
  | publisher =[[Vanity Fair]]
  | date =August 1999
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/VanityFair.pdf 
  | accessdate =  }}
See </ref><ref>http://www.laboractionmumia.org/docs/021_YohnRuling.rtf December 2001 US District Court ruling of Judge Yohn which relates "[Abu-Jamal] was heard to twice say that “I shot the [[motherfucker]], and I hope the motherfucker dies.”</ref>}} 

Contrary to those witnesses, some witnesses are recorded as having reported that he was completely [[unconscious]] during the time that he was reported to have uttered it.<ref>http://www.freemumia.org/intro.html ''Who is mumia?'' from mumia.org incorporating the statement "Abu-Jamal's doctor said that Abu-Jamal, who was unconscious, said nothing. He reported that a nurse found police with loaded guns pointed at Mumia as he lay unconscious in his hospital bed."</ref> 

The original report of Gary Wakshul, a police officer who confirms to having accompanied him throughout the entire period of his arrest and medical treatment, states that he "made no comment." Officer Wakshul elsewhere later stated that he witnessed Abu-Jamal's utterance of the "hospital bed" confession on the night of the killing, such statement being made almost three months after the arrest and upon the occasion when the [[prosecutor]] met with police seeking to test the evidence about Abu-Jamal's alleged utterance of it. Wakshul is recorded as having reasoned that he "didn't think the confession was important" at the time he wrote his original report.<ref name= "MAJCRD_DVD">{{cite video
| people = Mumia Abu-Jamal
| title = Mumia Abu-Jamal: A Case for Reasonable Doubt? 
| medium = DVD of HBO TV Special
| publisher = Otmoor Productions
| location = London, UK
| date = 1997 }}</ref> Judge [[Albert F. Sabo]] did not permit the trial [[jury]] to receive Gary Wakshul's original report as evidence.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =1982 trial transcripts
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
 </ref>

=== Witnesses not called at trial ===
{{seealso|Mumia Abu-Jamal legal proceedings#New witnesses}}
Several material and potentially material witnesses were not called to testify at trial. Some were subsequently heard from at Post-Conviction Review Act hearings in the period 1995-7 or otherwise had their statements incorporated into appeal briefs filed on behalf of Abu-Jamal. 

Abu-Jamal did not testify in his own defense. Regarding this he has explained:<blockquote>"At my trial I was denied the [[right]] to [[self-defense|defend myself]]. I had no confidence in my [[public defender|court-appointed attorney]], who never even asked me what happened the night I was shot and the police officer was killed; and I was excluded from at least half the trial. ''Since I was denied all my rights at my trial I did not testify. I would not be used to make it look like I had a fair trial''."<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Declaration of Mumia Abu-Jamal
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =May 2001
  | url =http://www.chicagofreemumia.org/mumiadecl.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref></blockquote>
It has been noted that Abu-Jamal was removed from the courtroom at least 13 times during the course of the legal proceedings and trial in 1982 by reason of deemed intentional disruptive actions.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Danielfaulkner.com summary of case facts (see pp.3,104)
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/SummaryofCaseFacts.pdf
  | format =PDF
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>

He did not state his version of events for the initial [[police]] [[investigation]], nor for almost another 20 years afterwards until subsequent to his third set of [[lawyer]]s offering the 1999 [[affidavit]] of [[Arnold Beverly]]. Beverly purported to [[Confession (legal)|confess]] that he was in fact the person who had shot Daniel Faulkner as part of a [[contract killing]] connected with a desire to keep the latter from interfering with [[political corruption|graft and payoffs]] to [[police corruption|corrupt police]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Affidavit of Arnold Beverly
  | work =
  | publisher =Free Mumia Coalition
  | date =June 8, 1999 
  | url =http://www.freemumia.com/beverlydeclaration.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> 

His May 2001 [[oath|sworn]] statement [[wikt:aver|avers]] that he had been sitting in his cab across the street when he heard the sound of gunshots. He asserted that, upon seeing his brother standing in the street staggering and appearing disoriented he ran across the street to him and was shot by a uniformed police officer. He also claimed he was [[torture]]d by the police before receiving medical aid.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Declaration of Mumia Abu-Jamal
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =May 3, 2001 
  | url =http://www.freemumia.com/beverlydeclaration.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

For a similar period, William Cook also did not [[testimony|testify]] or make any statement whatsoever about the event other than to deny his own involvement in the shooting. On April 29, 2001, he belatedly authored a declaration to the effect that he would be willing to testify and that both he and his brother "had nothing do with shooting or killing the policeman".<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Declaration of William Cook
  | work =
  | publisher =Free Mumia Coalition
  | date =April 29, 2001
  | url =http://www.freemumia.com/cookdeclaration.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

William Singletary has stated that he directly witnessed the entire incident and that he would be willing to testify that Abu-Jamal was not the gunman.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last ="Minister of Information JR"    
  | first =
  | coauthors =
  | title =William Singletary, eyewitness on the night Mumia was shot and framed - Part 2
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =San Francisco Bay View
  | date =June 19, 2007
  | url =http://www.sfbayview.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=229&Itemid=18 
  | accessdate =  }}
Interview with William Singletary published 19 June 2007</ref> Singletary's Post-Conviction Review Act hearing testimony of August 11, 1995 described that police tore up two of his written statements and that he was prevailed upon to sign a different statement which they dictated.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Kissinger
  | first =C. Clark 
  | coauthors =
  | title =Analysis of the Pennsylvania Supreme Court Decision On Mumia Abu-Jamal
  | work =Revolutionary Worker #982
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =Revolutionary Worker 
  | date =November 15, 1998
  | url =http://www.rwor.org/a/v20/980-89/982/court.htm  
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

[[Image:Singchair.jpg|thumb|right|A model of [[electric chair]]. Electrocution was an authorised means for the execution of condemned prisoners in Pennsylvania until November 29, 1990.<ref>>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Historical information on the death penalty and executions in Pennsylvania 
  | work =
  | publisher =Pennsylvania Department of Corrections
  | date = 
  | url =http://www.cor.state.pa.us/deathpenalty/site/default.asp?portalNav=|
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>]] Court stenographer Terri Maurer-Carter stated in an affidavit of August 2001 that in the presence of herself and two others the presiding Judge had exclaimed:
{{cquote|"Yeah, and I'm going to help them [[electric chair|fry]] the [[nigger]]."<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Statement of Terri Maurer-Carter
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =August 21, 2001 
  | url =http://www.labournet.net/mumia/0109/terrimc.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>}}regarding Abu-Jamal's case shortly before the start of the trial.

On April 24, 2003, Kenneth Pate, the step-brother of Priscilla Durham, swore a declaration incorporating the following relevant content:<blockquote>"I read a newspaper article about the Mumia Abu-Jamal case. It said Priscilla Durham had testified at Abu-Jamal's trial that when she was working as a security guard at the hospital she heard Abu-Jamal say that he had killed the police officer. When I read this I realized it was a different story from what she had told me.” .. [when I asked her] .. "Did you hear him say that?”" [she] answered, "All I heard him say was: 'Get off me, get off me, they're trying to kill me'."<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Declaration of Kenneth Pate
  | work =
  | publisher =Free Mumia Coalition
  | date =April 18, 2003
  | url =http://www.mumia.de/doc/aktuell/20030510mde00en.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref></blockquote> 
Pate reported that the conversation occurred "sometime around the end of 1983 or the beginning of 1984", while he was in the same [[prison]] as Abu-Jamal. His affidavit was released during another period in which both he and Abu-Jamal were housed in the same prison - a time postdating the death of Ms Durham.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Declaration of Kenneth Pate
  | work =
  | publisher =Free Mumia Coalition
  | date =April 18, 2003
  | url =http://www.mumia.de/doc/aktuell/20030510mde00en.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> Pate's affidavit has been tendered as evidence by Abu-Jamal’s lawyers to the [[U.S. Court of Appeals]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Brief on behalf of Mumia Abu-Jamal to the US Court of Appeal
  | work =
