  | url =http://www.freemumia.com/pdfs/julybrief.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>

=== Physical evidence === 
[[Image:44-cartridge.jpg|thumb|right|.44 caliber ammunition rounds]][[Image:Charter Arms Bulldog.JPG|thumb|250px|Charter Arms ''Bulldog'' Revolver (accomodating .44 Special rounds)]] 
A .38 [[caliber]] [[handgun]] he had [[purchase]]d to defend himself as a cab driver in 1979 was found at the scene next to him, containing 5 spent [[shell casings]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Developments in the Mumia Abu-Jamal case
  | work =
  | publisher =CNN.com/Law Center 
  | date =
  | url =http://archives.cnn.com/2001/LAW/12/18/chronology.abu.jamal 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Mumia Reconsidered
  | work =
  | publisher =DC Indymedia 
  | date =November 6, 1998
  | url =http://dc.indymedia.org/newswire/display/110698/index.php 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> [[Coroner]] Dr. Paul Hoyer, who [[autopsy|autopsied]] Daniel Faulkner, contemporaneously recorded that he extracted a [[.44 Magnum|.44 caliber]] [[bullet]] noting  "shot w/ 44 cal". He later testified to the effect that his description of it had been a "rough guess" based on his own observations, that he was not a [[firearms]] expert and that he had not received any training in weapons ballistics.<ref>Trial transcipt for June 25, 1982.</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last =Kissinger
  | first =C. Clark 
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Building a Railroad:
The Suppression, Manipulation and
Fabrication of Evidence 
  | work =Revolutionary Worker #1044
  | publisher =Revolutionary Worker 
  | date =February 27, 2000
  | url =http://www.rwor.org/a/v21/1040-049/1044/habeas4.htm 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> 

Tests performed with the available physical evidence verify that Daniel Faulkner was killed by a .38 caliber bullet. The extracted slug identifies as a [[Federal Cartridge|Federal brand]] [[.38 Special]] [[+P]] bullet with a hollow base and it may be noted that the hollow base in a +P bullet is distinguishable from Federal [[ammunition]] used at that time.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =.38 Special LSWCHP +P: Still a Top Load? 
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.hipowersandhandguns.com/38%20Special%20158gr%20LSWCHP.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> The type, brand, and caliber of the extracted bullet all match those of the shell casings obtained from Abu-Jamal's [[Charter Arms]] [[revolver]] which was retrieved at the scene. That manufacturer is known for [[rifling]] the barrels of their revolvers with eight lands and grooves, variant to the six present in all other firearms.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Testimony of Anthony L. Paul, Supervisor Firearms Identification Unit, Philadelphia Police Department. 1982 trial transcripts at p.168 for June 23, 1982.
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>  

Experts testified that the bullet taken from Abu-Jamal had been fired from Daniel Faulkner's service weapon. George Fassnacht, a ballistics expert proferred by the defense, did not dispute any of the prosecution's findings.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =MUMIA ABU-JAMAL, Petitioner, v. MARTIN HORN, Commissioner, Pennsylvania Department of Corrections, ET AL., Respondents. Memorandum and Order
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.paed.uscourts.gov/documents/opinions/01D0951P.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> 

[[Amnesty International]] has made reference to the physical evidence to the extent of expressing their view that there was: <blockquote>".. a lack of adequate [[Ballistic fingerprinting|ballistic tests]] to determine whether [Abu-Jamal's] gun had recently been fired. It was not determined, for instance, whether there was [[gunshot residue|residue]] on his hands from firing a [[gun]]."<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =USA: Mumia Abu-Jamal -- Amnesty International calls for retrial
  | work =
  | publisher =Amnesty International, USA
  | date =
  | url =http://web.amnesty.org/library/Index/engAMR510202000 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref></blockquote>

In a 1995 hearing, a ballistics expert proffered by the defense testified that due to Abu-Jamal's struggle with the police during his arrest, such a test would have been difficult to accomplish and, due to the [[gunpowder]] residue possibly being shaken or rubbed off, would not have been scientifically reliable.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =COMMONWEALTH VS. MUMIA ABU-JAMAL aka WESLEY COOK - Post Conviction Review Act hearing transcripts of February 8, 1995
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/pcra/95-08-02.html 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> 

The jury delivered a guilty [[verdict]] after three hours of [[deliberation]]s.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Danielfaulkner.com summary of case facts (see p.2)
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/SummaryofCaseFacts.pdf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> In the sentencing phase of the trial Abu-Jamal read from a prepared statement without being sworn or examined by the attorney for either party, and he declined to call any mitigating witnesses.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =US District Court ruling of Judge Yohn
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =December 2001 
  | url =http://www.laboractionmumia.org/docs/021_YohnRuling.rtf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>

== Death sentence and reactions ==
[[Image:Free Mumia.jpg|thumb|200px|right|"Free Mumia" parking garage stencil with "Cop killer" [[graffito]].]][[Image:040705 009 bristol maj m32.jpg|thumb|An anarchist mural in inner-city [[Bristol]], [[England]]]]He was subsequently [[death sentence|sentenced to death]] by the [[unanimous]] [[decision]] of his jury<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Danielfaulkner.com summary of case facts (see p.3)
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/SummaryofCaseFacts.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }} </ref> on July 3, 1982.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =US District Court ruling of Judge Yohn
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =December 2001 
  | url =http://www.laboractionmumia.org/docs/021_YohnRuling.rtf 
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> The date of the sentence is recorded as May 25, 1983.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Persons sentenced to execution in Pennsylvania as of August 1, 2007
  | work =
  | publisher =Pennslyvania Department of Corrections
  | date =
  | url =http://www.cor.state.pa.us/portal/lib/portal/Execution_List.pdf
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =August 31, 2007}}</ref> Judicial execution in Pennsylvania is by means of [[lethal injection]] and would occur at the [[State Correctional Institution - Rockview]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Information re death penalty and executions in Pennsylvania
  | work =
  | publisher =Pennsylvania Department of Corrections 
  | date =
