== Life as a prisoner ==
=== Activism, writings, educational pursuits ===
Since imprisonment, he has continued his political activism, publishing ''[[Live from Death Row]]'', a book on life inside prisons. He has attained a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from [[Goddard College]] and a [[Master of Arts (postgraduate)|Master of Arts]] from [[California State University, Dominguez Hills]], both by [[distance education]]. The [http://newcollege.edu/law/index.cfm New College of California School of Law] has presented him with a [[J.D.]] degree.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =New College of California School of Law - list of honorary degree recipients
  | work =
  | publisher =
  | date =
  | url =http://www.newcollege.edu/law/honorary_degrees.cfm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>

=== 1992 confession ===
In 1999, ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' revealed that Phillip Bloch visited him in prison in 1992 and asked him whether he regretted killing Faulkner, to which it was reported that he replied: {{cquote|"Yes."<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Bissinger
  | first =Buzz 
  | coauthors =
  | title =The Famous And The Dead
  | work =
  | pages =6
  | language =
  | publisher =Vanity Fair
  | date =August 1999
  | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/VanityFair.pdf 
  | accessdate =  }}
See p.6</ref>}}
Bloch, otherwise a supporter of his case, stated he came forward after he grew concerned about the [[Character assassination|vilification]] of Daniel Faulkner. In response, Abu-Jamal is reported to have said "A lie is a lie, whether made today or 10 years later", and thanked ''Vanity Fair'' "...not for their work but for stoking this controversy, because controversy leads to questioning, and one can only question this belated confession."<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =Mackler
  | first =Jeff 
  | coauthors =
  | title =Vanity Fair and ABC-TV Stories of Mumia's 'Confession' Collapse
  | work =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =Socialist Action
  | date =August 1999
  | url =http://www.socialistaction.org/news/199908/confession.html 
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>

=== "Public speaking" ===
